# Release Announcements

Use this approach when drafting release messaging for an Ycode release (X thread, Discord post).
Always read the full GitHub release / PR descriptions first so the announcement names real UI labels, button names, and behaviors — never abstract marketing terms.

## X (Twitter) Thread

Voice: declarative, present tense, concrete. No hashtags. No emoji except `🧵` in the opener. No "We're excited to announce…". No marketing puffery.

### Structure

1. **Opener (Tweet 1)** — version + the ONE headline change in a single short line, then a one-line "why it matters", then `🧵` on its own line.
   - Example: `Ycode 1.5.0 is out.\n\nYou can now translate your site directly on the builder canvas.\n\nSwitch the locale, and the canvas becomes a real translation surface — no more juggling a separate panel.\n\n🧵`
2. **Body tweets** — ONE idea per tweet. Lead with the change, follow with the concrete user-visible detail. Short paragraphs (1–3 lines each).
3. **Closer (final tweet)** — exactly this shape:
   ```
   Ycode is open source. Self-host it or use the managed cloud.

   Release: https://github.com/ycode/ycode/releases/tag/<version>
   Docs: https://docs.ycode.com/docs/<relevant-section>
   ```

### Writing rules

- Name real UI: button labels (`Save translation`), tab names (`Design`, `Interactions`), field types (`text`, `rich text`), sub-labels (`IMAGE`, `IMAGE ALT`, `VIDEO`). Quote them verbatim — usually in **bold**.
- Use before/after framing: "No more X. Just Y." / "…step out of the way." / "…stays in sync."
- Prefer concrete enumerations over generic words ("text, rich text, images, and CMS values" beats "all your content").
- Keep each tweet under ~280 chars; if it spills, split.
- Don't number tweets inline (`1/`, `2/`) — the platform/threading handles order. (If the user explicitly wants numbering, add `**N/**` at the start.)
- Don't summarize the thread at the end. The closer is just the OSS line + links.

## Discord Post (#announcements)

Voice: friendlier than X, still concrete. Emojis are encouraged here — one per bullet, plus a header emoji and a closing emoji. Don't stack multiple emojis.

### Structure

1. **Header line**: `🌍 **Ycode <version> — <one-line headline>**` (pick a header emoji that matches the feature).
2. **Lede**: 1–2 sentences expanding the headline, optionally ending with a single ✨-style flourish.
3. **`**What's new**` section**: bulleted list. Each bullet starts with a relevant emoji (🌐 🪄 🏷️ 📝 🗂️ 🎯 🔒 🚀 etc.), then the change, then the concrete detail. Mirror the X body but allow more breathing room.
4. **Links block**:
   ```
   📚 Updated docs: https://docs.ycode.com/docs/<section>
   📦 Full release notes: https://github.com/ycode/ycode/releases/tag/<version>
   ```
5. **Sign-off**: one short upbeat line + a single emoji (e.g. `Happy translating! 🎉`).

Wrap the whole post in a single fenced code block so the user can copy it cleanly.

## Both formats — non-negotiables

- Read the GitHub release notes and the linked PR(s) before drafting. Pull behavior, gate conditions, and exact UI strings from the source.
- Mention what's locked / disabled / hidden when relevant — Ycode releases often improve things by *removing* friction, and that should be visible.
- If the release ships docs updates, link the updated docs page (not just the section root) when there's a deep link that fits.
- Never invent features or UI strings. If the source is ambiguous, omit the detail rather than guess.
